 1354","about 1355":"circa 1355","1419":"1419","Clopton, Gloucestershire, England":"Clopton, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1355–":"about 1355–Deceased","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","1350–1384":"1350–1384","1387–1419":"1387–1419","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","about 1387":"about 1387","about 1354":"about 1354","about 1355":"about 1355","1419":"1419","Clopton, Gloucestershire, England":"Clopton, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Charlton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from North Charlton or Charlton near Bellingham (both Northumberland) or from any of the many other places so named (there are over ninety examples in England), from Old English <i>Ceorlatūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlton","meanings":["English (northern and eastern England): habitational name from any of various places called Carlton (Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Durham, Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Northamptonshire, Suffolk, East Yorkshire, Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire) or Carleton (Cumberland, Lancashire, Norfolk, Yorkshire). All come from Old Norse <i>karl</i> ‘common man, peasant’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’ (compare   Charlton  ). Places spelled <i>Carl(e)ton</i> (as opposed to <i>Charlton</i>) are in areas of Scandinavian settlement, mostly in northern England.","Irish (Antrim): variant of   Carleton   2."]},{"name":"Carlin","meanings":["Irish (North Ulster; now also common in Scotland): from <b>Ó Cearbhalláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cearbhallán</i>’, a diminutive of the personal name <i>Cearbhall</i> (see   Carroll  ).","English: variant of   Carling  .","Italian (Veneto): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, Italian form of   Charles  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":100,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary de Charlton was born about 1355, in Gloucestershire, England, her father, Roger de Charlton, was 27 and her mother, Elizabeth le Beisine, was 22. She married John de Clopton in 1379, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1355–":"umbes 1355–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1350–1384":"1350–1384","1387–1419":"1387–1419","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","about 1387":"umbes 1387","about 1354":"umbes 1354","about 1355":"umbes 1355","1419":"1419","Clopton, Gloucestershire, England":"Clopton, Gloucestersh